101struct basic_cb_args
102{
103 struct event_base *eb;
104 struct event *ev;
105 unsigned int callcount;
106};

108static void
109simple_read_cb(evutil_socket_t fd, short event, void *arg)
110{
111 char buf[256];
112 int len;
113
114 len = read(fd, buf, sizeof(buf));
115
116 if (len) {
117 if (!called) {
118 if (event_add(arg, NULL) == -1)
119 exit(1);
120 }
121 } else if (called == 1)
122 test_ok = 1;
123
124 called++;
125}
126
127static void
128basic_read_cb(evutil_socket_t fd, short event, void *data)
129{
130 char buf[256];
131 int len;
132 struct basic_cb_args *arg = data;
133
134 len = read(fd, buf, sizeof(buf));
135
136 if (len < 0) {
137 tt_fail_perror("read (callback)");
138 } else {
139 switch (arg->callcount++) {
140 case 0: /* first call: expect to read data; cycle */
141 if (len > 0)
142 return;
143
144 tt_fail_msg("EOF before data read");
145 break;
146
147 case 1: /* second call: expect EOF; stop */
148 if (len > 0)
149 tt_fail_msg("not all data read on first cycle");
150 break;
151
152 default: /* third call: should not happen */
153 tt_fail_msg("too many cycles");
154 }
155 }
156
157 event_del(arg->ev);
158 event_base_loopexit(arg->eb, NULL);
159}

167simple_write_cb(evutil_socket_t fd, short event, void *arg)

172 if (len == -1)

175 test_ok = 1;

178static void
179multiple_write_cb(evutil_socket_t fd, short event, void *arg)
180{
181 struct event *ev = arg;
182 int len;
183
184 len = 128;
185 if (woff + len >= (int)sizeof(wbuf))
186 len = sizeof(wbuf) - woff;
187
188 len = write(fd, wbuf + woff, len);
189 if (len == -1) {
190 fprintf(stderr, "%s: write\n", __func__);
191 if (usepersist)
192 event_del(ev);
193 return;
194 }
195
196 woff += len;
197
198 if (woff >= (int)sizeof(wbuf)) {
199 shutdown(fd, EVUTIL_SHUT_WR);
200 if (usepersist)
201 event_del(ev);
202 return;
203 }
204
205 if (!usepersist) {
206 if (event_add(ev, NULL) == -1)
207 exit(1);
208 }
209}

211static void
212multiple_read_cb(evutil_socket_t fd, short event, void *arg)
213{
214 struct event *ev = arg;
215 int len;
216
217 len = read(fd, rbuf + roff, sizeof(rbuf) - roff);
218 if (len == -1)
219 fprintf(stderr, "%s: read\n", __func__);
220 if (len <= 0) {
221 if (usepersist)
222 event_del(ev);
223 return;
224 }
225
226 roff += len;
227 if (!usepersist) {
228 if (event_add(ev, NULL) == -1)
229 exit(1);
230 }
231}

239struct both {
240 struct event ev;
241 int nread;
242};
243
244static void
245combined_read_cb(evutil_socket_t fd, short event, void *arg)
246{
247 struct both *both = arg;
248 char buf[128];
249 int len;
250
251 len = read(fd, buf, sizeof(buf));
252 if (len == -1)
253 fprintf(stderr, "%s: read\n", __func__);
254 if (len <= 0)
255 return;
256
257 both->nread += len;
258 if (event_add(&both->ev, NULL) == -1)
259 exit(1);
260}
261
262static void
263combined_write_cb(evutil_socket_t fd, short event, void *arg)
264{
265 struct both *both = arg;
266 char buf[128];
267 int len;
268
269 len = sizeof(buf);
270 if (len > both->nread)
271 len = both->nread;
272
273 memset(buf, 'q', len);
274
275 len = write(fd, buf, len);
276 if (len == -1)
277 fprintf(stderr, "%s: write\n", __func__);
278 if (len <= 0) {
279 shutdown(fd, EVUTIL_SHUT_WR);
280 return;
281 }
282
283 both->nread -= len;
284 if (event_add(&both->ev, NULL) == -1)
285 exit(1);
286}

288/* These macros used to replicate the work of the legacy test wrapper code */
289#define setup_test(x) do { \
290 if (!in_legacy_test_wrapper) { \
291 TT_FAIL(("Legacy test %s not wrapped properly", x)); \
292 return; \
293 } \
294 } while (0)
295#define cleanup_test() setup_test("cleanup")

297static void
298test_simpleread(void)
299{
300 struct event ev;
301
302 /* Very simple read test */
303 setup_test("Simple read: ");
304
305 if (write(pair[0], TEST1, strlen(TEST1)+1) < 0) {
306 tt_fail_perror("write");
307 }
308
309 shutdown(pair[0], EVUTIL_SHUT_WR);
310
311 event_set(&ev, pair[1], EV_READ, simple_read_cb, &ev);
312 if (event_add(&ev, NULL) == -1)
313 exit(1);
314 event_dispatch();
315
316 cleanup_test();
317}

367static int have_closed = 0;
368static int premature_event = 0;
369static void
370simpleclose_close_fd_cb(evutil_socket_t s, short what, void *ptr)
371{
372 evutil_socket_t **fds = ptr;
373 TT_BLATHER(("Closing"));
374 evutil_closesocket(*fds[0]);
375 evutil_closesocket(*fds[1]);
376 *fds[0] = -1;
377 *fds[1] = -1;
378 have_closed = 1;
379}
380
381static void
382record_event_cb(evutil_socket_t s, short what, void *ptr)
383{
384 short *whatp = ptr;
385 if (!have_closed)
386 premature_event = 1;
387 *whatp = what;
388 TT_BLATHER(("Recorded %d on socket %d", (int)what, (int)s));
389}
390
391static void
392test_simpleclose(void *ptr)
393{
394 /* Test that a close of FD is detected as a read and as a write. */
395 struct event_base *base = event_base_new();
396 evutil_socket_t pair1[2]={-1,-1}, pair2[2] = {-1, -1};
397 evutil_socket_t *to_close[2];
398 struct event *rev=NULL, *wev=NULL, *closeev=NULL;
399 struct timeval tv;
400 short got_read_on_close = 0, got_write_on_close = 0;
401 char buf[1024];
402 memset(buf, 99, sizeof(buf));
403#ifdef _WIN32
404#define LOCAL_SOCKETPAIR_AF AF_INET
405#else
406#define LOCAL_SOCKETPAIR_AF AF_UNIX
407#endif
408 if (evutil_socketpair(LOCAL_SOCKETPAIR_AF, SOCK_STREAM, 0, pair1)<0)
409 TT_DIE(("socketpair: %s", strerror(errno)));
410 if (evutil_socketpair(LOCAL_SOCKETPAIR_AF, SOCK_STREAM, 0, pair2)<0)
411 TT_DIE(("socketpair: %s", strerror(errno)));
412 if (evutil_make_socket_nonblocking(pair1[1]) < 0)
413 TT_DIE(("make_socket_nonblocking"));
414 if (evutil_make_socket_nonblocking(pair2[1]) < 0)
415 TT_DIE(("make_socket_nonblocking"));
416
417 /** Stuff pair2[1] full of data, until write fails */
418 while (1) {
419 int r = write(pair2[1], buf, sizeof(buf));
420 if (r<0) {
421 int err = evutil_socket_geterror(pair2[1]);
422 if (! EVUTIL_ERR_RW_RETRIABLE(err))
423 TT_DIE(("write failed strangely: %s",
424 evutil_socket_error_to_string(err)));
425 break;
426 }
427 }
428 to_close[0] = &pair1[0];
429 to_close[1] = &pair2[0];
430
431 closeev = event_new(base, -1, EV_TIMEOUT, simpleclose_close_fd_cb,
432 to_close);
433 rev = event_new(base, pair1[1], EV_READ, record_event_cb,
434 &got_read_on_close);
435 TT_BLATHER(("Waiting for read on %d", (int)pair1[1]));
436 wev = event_new(base, pair2[1], EV_WRITE, record_event_cb,
437 &got_write_on_close);
438 TT_BLATHER(("Waiting for write on %d", (int)pair2[1]));
439 tv.tv_sec = 0;
440 tv.tv_usec = 100*1000; /* Close pair1[0] after a little while, and make
441 * sure we get a read event. */
442 event_add(closeev, &tv);
443 event_add(rev, NULL);
444 event_add(wev, NULL);
445 /* Don't let the test go on too long. */
446 tv.tv_sec = 0;
447 tv.tv_usec = 200*1000;
448 event_base_loopexit(base, &tv);
449 event_base_loop(base, 0);
450
451 tt_int_op(got_read_on_close, ==, EV_READ);
452 tt_int_op(got_write_on_close, ==, EV_WRITE);
453 tt_int_op(premature_event, ==, 0);
454
455end:
456 if (pair1[0] >= 0)
457 evutil_closesocket(pair1[0]);
458 if (pair1[1] >= 0)
459 evutil_closesocket(pair1[1]);
460 if (pair2[0] >= 0)
461 evutil_closesocket(pair2[0]);
462 if (pair2[1] >= 0)
463 evutil_closesocket(pair2[1]);
464 if (rev)
465 event_free(rev);
466 if (wev)
467 event_free(wev);
468 if (closeev)
469 event_free(closeev);
470 if (base)
471 event_base_free(base);
472}

475static void
476test_multiple(void)
477{
478 struct event ev, ev2;
479 int i;
480
481 /* Multiple read and write test */
482 setup_test("Multiple read/write: ");
483 memset(rbuf, 0, sizeof(rbuf));
484 for (i = 0; i < (int)sizeof(wbuf); i++)
485 wbuf[i] = i;
486
487 roff = woff = 0;
488 usepersist = 0;
489
490 event_set(&ev, pair[0], EV_WRITE, multiple_write_cb, &ev);
491 if (event_add(&ev, NULL) == -1)
492 exit(1);
493 event_set(&ev2, pair[1], EV_READ, multiple_read_cb, &ev2);
494 if (event_add(&ev2, NULL) == -1)
495 exit(1);
496 event_dispatch();
497
498 if (roff == woff)
499 test_ok = memcmp(rbuf, wbuf, sizeof(wbuf)) == 0;
500
501 cleanup_test();
502}

505test_persistent(void)

523 if (event_add(&ev2, NULL) == -1)
524 exit(1);
525 event_dispatch();
526
527 if (roff == woff)
528 test_ok = memcmp(rbuf, wbuf, sizeof(wbuf)) == 0;
529
530 cleanup_test();
531}

533static void
534test_combined(void)
535{
536 struct both r1, r2, w1, w2;
537
538 setup_test("Combined read/write: ");
539 memset(&r1, 0, sizeof(r1));
540 memset(&r2, 0, sizeof(r2));
541 memset(&w1, 0, sizeof(w1));
542 memset(&w2, 0, sizeof(w2));
543
544 w1.nread = 4096;
545 w2.nread = 8192;
546
547 event_set(&r1.ev, pair[0], EV_READ, combined_read_cb, &r1);
548 event_set(&w1.ev, pair[0], EV_WRITE, combined_write_cb, &w1);
549 event_set(&r2.ev, pair[1], EV_READ, combined_read_cb, &r2);
550 event_set(&w2.ev, pair[1], EV_WRITE, combined_write_cb, &w2);
551 tt_assert(event_add(&r1.ev, NULL) != -1);
552 tt_assert(!event_add(&w1.ev, NULL));
553 tt_assert(!event_add(&r2.ev, NULL));
554 tt_assert(!event_add(&w2.ev, NULL));
555 event_dispatch();
556
557 if (r1.nread == 8192 && r2.nread == 4096)
558 test_ok = 1;
559
560end:
561 cleanup_test();
562}

565test_simpletimeout(void)
566{
567 struct timeval tv;

587static void
588periodic_timeout_cb(evutil_socket_t fd, short event, void *arg)
589{
590 int *count = arg;
591
592 (*count)++;
593 if (*count == 6) {
594 /* call loopexit only once - on slow machines(?), it is
595 * apparently possible for this to get called twice. */
596 test_ok = 1;
597 event_base_loopexit(global_base, NULL);
598 }
599}

620static void
621test_persistent_timeout_jump(void *ptr)
622{
623 struct basic_test_data *data = ptr;
624 struct event ev;
625 int count = 0;
626 struct timeval msec100 = { 0, 100 * 1000 };
627 struct timeval msec50 = { 0, 50 * 1000 };
628 struct timeval msec300 = { 0, 300 * 1000 };
629
630 event_assign(&ev, data->base, -1, EV_PERSIST, periodic_timeout_cb, &count);
631 event_add(&ev, &msec100);
632 /* Wait for a bit */
633 evutil_usleep_(&msec300);
634 event_base_loopexit(data->base, &msec50);
635 event_base_dispatch(data->base);
636 tt_int_op(count, ==, 1);
637
638end:
639 event_del(&ev);
640}

642struct persist_active_timeout_called {
643 int n;
644 short events[16];
645 struct timeval tvs[16];
646};
647
648static void
649activate_cb(evutil_socket_t fd, short event, void *arg)
650{
651 struct event *ev = arg;
652 event_active(ev, EV_READ, 1);
653}
654
655static void
656persist_active_timeout_cb(evutil_socket_t fd, short event, void *arg)
657{
658 struct persist_active_timeout_called *c = arg;
659 if (c->n < 15) {
660 c->events[c->n] = event;
661 evutil_gettimeofday(&c->tvs[c->n], NULL);
662 ++c->n;
663 }
664}
665
666static void
667test_persistent_active_timeout(void *ptr)
668{
669 struct timeval tv, tv2, tv_exit, start;
670 struct event ev;
671 struct persist_active_timeout_called res;
672
673 struct basic_test_data *data = ptr;
674 struct event_base *base = data->base;
675
676 memset(&res, 0, sizeof(res));
677
678 tv.tv_sec = 0;
679 tv.tv_usec = 200 * 1000;
680 event_assign(&ev, base, -1, EV_TIMEOUT|EV_PERSIST,
681 persist_active_timeout_cb, &res);
682 event_add(&ev, &tv);
683
684 tv2.tv_sec = 0;
685 tv2.tv_usec = 100 * 1000;
686 event_base_once(base, -1, EV_TIMEOUT, activate_cb, &ev, &tv2);
687
688 tv_exit.tv_sec = 0;
689 tv_exit.tv_usec = 600 * 1000;
690 event_base_loopexit(base, &tv_exit);
691
692 event_base_assert_ok_(base);
693 evutil_gettimeofday(&start, NULL);
694
695 event_base_dispatch(base);
696 event_base_assert_ok_(base);
697
698 tt_int_op(res.n, ==, 3);
699 tt_int_op(res.events[0], ==, EV_READ);
700 tt_int_op(res.events[1], ==, EV_TIMEOUT);
701 tt_int_op(res.events[2], ==, EV_TIMEOUT);
702 test_timeval_diff_eq(&start, &res.tvs[0], 100);
703 test_timeval_diff_eq(&start, &res.tvs[1], 300);
704 test_timeval_diff_eq(&start, &res.tvs[2], 500);
705end:
706 event_del(&ev);
707}

709struct common_timeout_info {
710 struct event ev;
711 struct timeval called_at;
712 int which;
713 int count;
714};
715
716static void
717common_timeout_cb(evutil_socket_t fd, short event, void *arg)
718{
719 struct common_timeout_info *ti = arg;
720 ++ti->count;
721 evutil_gettimeofday(&ti->called_at, NULL);
722 if (ti->count >= 4)
723 event_del(&ti->ev);
724}
725
726static void
727test_common_timeout(void *ptr)
728{
729 struct basic_test_data *data = ptr;
730
731 struct event_base *base = data->base;
732 int i;
733 struct common_timeout_info info[100];
734
735 struct timeval start;
736 struct timeval tmp_100_ms = { 0, 100*1000 };
737 struct timeval tmp_200_ms = { 0, 200*1000 };
738 struct timeval tmp_5_sec = { 5, 0 };
739 struct timeval tmp_5M_usec = { 0, 5*1000*1000 };
740
741 const struct timeval *ms_100, *ms_200, *sec_5;
742
743 ms_100 = event_base_init_common_timeout(base, &tmp_100_ms);
744 ms_200 = event_base_init_common_timeout(base, &tmp_200_ms);
745 sec_5 = event_base_init_common_timeout(base, &tmp_5_sec);
746 tt_assert(ms_100);
747 tt_assert(ms_200);
748 tt_assert(sec_5);
749 tt_ptr_op(event_base_init_common_timeout(base, &tmp_200_ms),
750 ==, ms_200);
751 tt_ptr_op(event_base_init_common_timeout(base, ms_200), ==, ms_200);
752 tt_ptr_op(event_base_init_common_timeout(base, &tmp_5M_usec), ==, sec_5);
753 tt_int_op(ms_100->tv_sec, ==, 0);
754 tt_int_op(ms_200->tv_sec, ==, 0);
755 tt_int_op(sec_5->tv_sec, ==, 5);
756 tt_int_op(ms_100->tv_usec, ==, 100000|0x50000000);
757 tt_int_op(ms_200->tv_usec, ==, 200000|0x50100000);
758 tt_int_op(sec_5->tv_usec, ==, 0|0x50200000);
759
760 memset(info, 0, sizeof(info));
761
762 for (i=0; i<100; ++i) {
763 info[i].which = i;
764 event_assign(&info[i].ev, base, -1, EV_TIMEOUT|EV_PERSIST,
765 common_timeout_cb, &info[i]);
766 if (i % 2) {
767 if ((i%20)==1) {
768 /* Glass-box test: Make sure we survive the
769 * transition to non-common timeouts. It's
770 * a little tricky. */
771 event_add(&info[i].ev, ms_200);
772 event_add(&info[i].ev, &tmp_100_ms);
773 } else if ((i%20)==3) {
774 /* Check heap-to-common too. */
775 event_add(&info[i].ev, &tmp_200_ms);
776 event_add(&info[i].ev, ms_100);
777 } else if ((i%20)==5) {
778 /* Also check common-to-common. */
779 event_add(&info[i].ev, ms_200);
780 event_add(&info[i].ev, ms_100);
781 } else {
782 event_add(&info[i].ev, ms_100);
783 }
784 } else {
785 event_add(&info[i].ev, ms_200);
786 }
787 }
788
789 event_base_assert_ok_(base);
790 evutil_gettimeofday(&start, NULL);
791 event_base_dispatch(base);
792
793 event_base_assert_ok_(base);
794
795 for (i=0; i<10; ++i) {
796 tt_int_op(info[i].count, ==, 4);
797 if (i % 2) {
798 test_timeval_diff_eq(&start, &info[i].called_at, 400);
799 } else {
800 test_timeval_diff_eq(&start, &info[i].called_at, 800);
801 }
802 }
803
804 /* Make sure we can free the base with some events in. */
805 for (i=0; i<100; ++i) {
806 if (i % 2) {
807 event_add(&info[i].ev, ms_100);
808 } else {
809 event_add(&info[i].ev, ms_200);
810 }
811 }
812
813end:
814 event_base_free(data->base); /* need to do this here before info is
815 * out-of-scope */
816 data->base = NULL;
817}

842 if (!called) {

852#define TEST_FORK_EXIT_SUCCESS 76
853static void fork_wait_check(int pid)
854{
855 int status;
856
857 TT_BLATHER(("Before waitpid"));
858
859#ifdef WNOWAIT
860 if ((waitpid(pid, &status, WNOWAIT) == -1 && errno == EINVAL) &&
861#else
862 if (
863#endif
864 waitpid(pid, &status, 0) == -1) {
865 perror("waitpid");
866 exit(1);
867 }
868 TT_BLATHER(("After waitpid"));
869
870 if (WEXITSTATUS(status) != TEST_FORK_EXIT_SUCCESS) {
871 fprintf(stdout, "FAILED (exit): %d\n", WEXITSTATUS(status));
872 exit(1);
873 }
874}
875static void
876test_fork(void)
877{
878 char c;
879 struct event ev, sig_ev, usr_ev, existing_ev;
880 pid_t pid;
881
882 setup_test("After fork: ");
883
884 {
885 if (evutil_socketpair(AF_UNIX, SOCK_STREAM, 0, child_pair) == -1) {
886 fprintf(stderr, "%s: socketpair\n", __func__);
887 exit(1);
888 }
889
890 if (evutil_make_socket_nonblocking(child_pair[0]) == -1) {
891 fprintf(stderr, "fcntl(O_NONBLOCK)");
892 exit(1);
893 }
894 }
895
896 tt_assert(current_base);
897 evthread_make_base_notifiable(current_base);
898
899 if (write(pair[0], TEST1, strlen(TEST1)+1) < 0) {
900 tt_fail_perror("write");
901 }
902
903 event_set(&ev, pair[1], EV_READ, simple_child_read_cb, &ev);
904 if (event_add(&ev, NULL) == -1)
905 exit(1);
906
907 evsignal_set(&sig_ev, SIGCHLD, fork_signal_cb, &sig_ev);
908 evsignal_add(&sig_ev, NULL);
909
910 evsignal_set(&existing_ev, SIGUSR2, fork_signal_cb, &existing_ev);
911 evsignal_add(&existing_ev, NULL);
912
913 event_base_assert_ok_(current_base);
914 TT_BLATHER(("Before fork"));
915 if ((pid = regress_fork()) == 0) {
916 /* in the child */
917 TT_BLATHER(("In child, before reinit"));
918 event_base_assert_ok_(current_base);
919 if (event_reinit(current_base) == -1) {
920 fprintf(stdout, "FAILED (reinit)\n");
921 exit(1);
922 }
923 TT_BLATHER(("After reinit"));
924 event_base_assert_ok_(current_base);
925 TT_BLATHER(("After assert-ok"));
926
927 evsignal_del(&sig_ev);
928
929 evsignal_set(&usr_ev, SIGUSR1, fork_signal_cb, &usr_ev);
930 evsignal_add(&usr_ev, NULL);
931 raise(SIGUSR1);
932 raise(SIGUSR2);
933
934 called = 0;
935
936 event_dispatch();
937
938 event_base_free(current_base);
939
940 /* we do not send an EOF; simple_read_cb requires an EOF
941 * to set test_ok. we just verify that the callback was
942 * called. */
943 exit(test_ok != 0 || called != 2 ? -2 : TEST_FORK_EXIT_SUCCESS);
944 }
945
946 /** wait until client read first message */
947 if (read(child_pair[1], &c, 1) < 0) {
948 tt_fail_perror("read");
949 }
950 if (write(pair[0], TEST1, strlen(TEST1)+1) < 0) {
951 tt_fail_perror("write");
952 }
953
954 fork_wait_check(pid);
955
956 /* test that the current event loop still works */
957 if (write(pair[0], TEST1, strlen(TEST1)+1) < 0) {
958 fprintf(stderr, "%s: write\n", __func__);
959 }
960
961 shutdown(pair[0], EVUTIL_SHUT_WR);
962
963 evsignal_set(&usr_ev, SIGUSR1, fork_signal_cb, &usr_ev);
964 evsignal_add(&usr_ev, NULL);
965 raise(SIGUSR1);
966 raise(SIGUSR2);
967
968 event_dispatch();
969
970 evsignal_del(&sig_ev);
971 tt_int_op(test_ok, ==, 1);
972
973 end:
974 cleanup_test();
975 if (child_pair[0] != -1)
976 evutil_closesocket(child_pair[0]);
977 if (child_pair[1] != -1)
978 evutil_closesocket(child_pair[1]);
979}

1183/*
1184 * make two bases to catch signals, use both of them. this only works
1185 * for event mechanisms that use our signal pipe trick. kqueue handles
1186 * signals internally, and all interested kqueues get all the signals.
1187 */
1188static void
1189test_signal_switchbase(void)
1190{
1191 struct event ev1, ev2;
1192 struct event_base *base1, *base2;
1193 int is_kqueue;
1194 test_ok = 0;
1195 base1 = event_init();
1196 base2 = event_init();
1197 is_kqueue = !strcmp(event_get_method(),"kqueue");
1198 evsignal_set(&ev1, SIGUSR1, signal_cb, &ev1);
1199 evsignal_set(&ev2, SIGUSR1, signal_cb, &ev2);
1200 if (event_base_set(base1, &ev1) ||
1201 event_base_set(base2, &ev2) ||
1202 event_add(&ev1, NULL) ||
1203 event_add(&ev2, NULL)) {
1204 fprintf(stderr, "%s: cannot set base, add\n", __func__);
1205 exit(1);
1206 }
1207
1208 tt_ptr_op(event_get_base(&ev1), ==, base1);
1209 tt_ptr_op(event_get_base(&ev2), ==, base2);
1210
1211 test_ok = 0;
1212 /* can handle signal before loop is called */
1213 raise(SIGUSR1);
1214 event_base_loop(base2, EVLOOP_NONBLOCK);
1215 if (is_kqueue) {
1216 if (!test_ok)
1217 goto end;
1218 test_ok = 0;
1219 }
1220 event_base_loop(base1, EVLOOP_NONBLOCK);
1221 if (test_ok && !is_kqueue) {
1222 test_ok = 0;
1223
1224 /* set base1 to handle signals */
1225 event_base_loop(base1, EVLOOP_NONBLOCK);
1226 raise(SIGUSR1);
1227 event_base_loop(base1, EVLOOP_NONBLOCK);
1228 event_base_loop(base2, EVLOOP_NONBLOCK);
1229 }
1230end:
1231 event_base_free(base1);
1232 event_base_free(base2);
1233 cleanup_test();
1234}

1258 /* XXXX Now there's no longer a good way. */

1273 * assert that we restore our previous signal handler properly.
1274 */
1275static void
1276test_signal_restore(void)
1277{
1278 struct event ev;
1279 struct event_base *base = event_init();
1280#ifdef EVENT__HAVE_SIGACTION
1281 struct sigaction sa;
1282#endif
1283
1284 test_ok = 0;
1285#ifdef EVENT__HAVE_SIGACTION
1286 sa.sa_handler = signal_cb_sa;
1287 sa.sa_flags = 0x0;
1288 sigemptyset(&sa.sa_mask);
1289 if (sigaction(SIGUSR1, &sa, NULL) == -1)
1290 goto out;

1293 goto out;

1297 evsignal_del(&ev);
1298
1299 raise(SIGUSR1);
1300 /* 1 == signal_cb, 2 == signal_cb_sa, we want our previous handler */
1301 if (test_ok != 2)
1302 test_ok = 0;
1303out:
1304 event_base_free(base);
1305 cleanup_test();
1306 return;

1442static void
1443test_event_base_get_num_events(void *ptr)
1444{
1445 struct basic_test_data *data = ptr;
1446 struct event_base *base = data->base;
1447 struct event ev;
1448 int event_count_active;
1449 int event_count_virtual;
1450 int event_count_added;
1451 int event_count_active_virtual;
1452 int event_count_active_added;
1453 int event_count_virtual_added;
1454 int event_count_active_added_virtual;
1455
1456 struct timeval qsec = {0, 100000};
1457
1458 event_assign(&ev, base, -1, EV_READ, event_selfarg_cb,
1459 event_self_cbarg());
1460
1461 event_add(&ev, &qsec);
1462 event_count_active = event_base_get_num_events(base,
1463 EVENT_BASE_COUNT_ACTIVE);
1464 event_count_virtual = event_base_get_num_events(base,
1465 EVENT_BASE_COUNT_VIRTUAL);
1466 event_count_added = event_base_get_num_events(base,
1467 EVENT_BASE_COUNT_ADDED);
1468 event_count_active_virtual = event_base_get_num_events(base,
1469 EVENT_BASE_COUNT_ACTIVE|EVENT_BASE_COUNT_VIRTUAL);
1470 event_count_active_added = event_base_get_num_events(base,
1471 EVENT_BASE_COUNT_ACTIVE|EVENT_BASE_COUNT_ADDED);
1472 event_count_virtual_added = event_base_get_num_events(base,
1473 EVENT_BASE_COUNT_VIRTUAL|EVENT_BASE_COUNT_ADDED);
1474 event_count_active_added_virtual = event_base_get_num_events(base,
1475 EVENT_BASE_COUNT_ACTIVE|
1476 EVENT_BASE_COUNT_ADDED|
1477 EVENT_BASE_COUNT_VIRTUAL);
1478 tt_int_op(event_count_active, ==, 0);
1479 tt_int_op(event_count_virtual, ==, 0);
1480 /* libevent itself adds a timeout event, so the event_count is 2 here */
1481 tt_int_op(event_count_added, ==, 2);
1482 tt_int_op(event_count_active_virtual, ==, 0);
1483 tt_int_op(event_count_active_added, ==, 2);
1484 tt_int_op(event_count_virtual_added, ==, 2);
1485 tt_int_op(event_count_active_added_virtual, ==, 2);

1785static void
1786test_active_later(void *ptr)
1787{
1788 struct basic_test_data *data = ptr;
1789 struct event *ev1 = NULL, *ev2 = NULL;
1790 struct event ev3, ev4;
1791 struct timeval qsec = {0, 100000};
1792 ev1 = event_new(data->base, data->pair[0], EV_READ|EV_PERSIST, read_and_drain_cb, NULL);
1793 ev2 = event_new(data->base, data->pair[1], EV_WRITE|EV_PERSIST, write_a_byte_cb, NULL);
1794 event_assign(&ev3, data->base, -1, 0, activate_other_event_cb, &ev4);
1795 event_assign(&ev4, data->base, -1, 0, activate_other_event_cb, &ev3);
1796 event_add(ev1, NULL);
1797 event_add(ev2, NULL);
1798 event_active_later_(&ev3, EV_READ);
1799
1800 event_base_loopexit(data->base, &qsec);
1801
1802 event_base_loop(data->base, 0);
1803
1804 TT_BLATHER(("%d write calls, %d read calls, %d activate-other calls.",
1805 n_write_a_byte_cb, n_read_and_drain_cb, n_activate_other_event_cb));
1806 event_del(&ev3);
1807 event_del(&ev4);
1808
1809 tt_int_op(n_write_a_byte_cb, ==, n_activate_other_event_cb);
1810 tt_int_op(n_write_a_byte_cb, >, 100);
1811 tt_int_op(n_read_and_drain_cb, >, 100);
1812 tt_int_op(n_activate_other_event_cb, >, 100);
1813
1814 event_active_later_(&ev4, EV_READ);
1815 event_active(&ev4, EV_READ, 1); /* This should make the event
1816 active immediately. */
1817 tt_assert((ev4.ev_flags & EVLIST_ACTIVE) != 0);
1818 tt_assert((ev4.ev_flags & EVLIST_ACTIVE_LATER) == 0);
1819
1820 /* Now leave this one around, so that event_free sees it and removes
1821 * it. */
1822 event_active_later_(&ev3, EV_READ);
1823 event_base_assert_ok_(data->base);
1824
1825end:
1826 if (ev1)
1827 event_free(ev1);
1828 if (ev2)
1829 event_free(ev2);
1830
1831 event_base_free(data->base);
1832 data->base = NULL;
1833}

1849static void send_a_byte_cb(evutil_socket_t fd, short what, void *arg)
1850{

1856struct read_not_timeout_param
1857{
1858 struct event **ev;
1859 int events;
1860 int count;
1861};
1862static void read_not_timeout_cb(evutil_socket_t fd, short what, void *arg)
1863{
1864 struct read_not_timeout_param *rntp = arg;
1865 char c;
1866 ev_ssize_t n;
1867 (void) fd; (void) what;
1868 n = read(fd, &c, 1);
1869 tt_int_op(n, ==, 1);
1870 rntp->events |= what;
1871 ++rntp->count;
1872 if(2 == rntp->count) event_del(rntp->ev[0]);
1873end:
1874 ;
1875}

1877static void
1878test_event_remove_timeout(void *ptr)
1879{
1880 struct basic_test_data *data = ptr;
1881 struct event_base *base = data->base;
1882 struct event *ev[5];
1883 int ev1_fired=0;
1884 struct timeval ms25 = { 0, 25*1000 },
1885 ms40 = { 0, 40*1000 },
1886 ms75 = { 0, 75*1000 },
1887 ms125 = { 0, 125*1000 };
1888 struct read_not_timeout_param rntp = { ev, 0, 0 };
1889
1890 event_base_assert_ok_(base);
1891
1892 ev[0] = event_new(base, data->pair[0], EV_READ|EV_PERSIST,
1893 read_not_timeout_cb, &rntp);
1894 ev[1] = evtimer_new(base, incr_arg_cb, &ev1_fired);
1895 ev[2] = evtimer_new(base, remove_timers_cb, ev);
1896 ev[3] = evtimer_new(base, send_a_byte_cb, &data->pair[1]);
1897 ev[4] = evtimer_new(base, send_a_byte_cb, &data->pair[1]);
1898 tt_assert(base);
1899 event_add(ev[2], &ms25); /* remove timers */
1900 event_add(ev[4], &ms40); /* write to test if timer re-activates */
1901 event_add(ev[0], &ms75); /* read */
1902 event_add(ev[1], &ms75); /* timer */
1903 event_add(ev[3], &ms125); /* timeout. */
1904 event_base_assert_ok_(base);
1905
1906 event_base_dispatch(base);
1907
1908 tt_int_op(ev1_fired, ==, 0);
1909 tt_int_op(rntp.events, ==, EV_READ);
1910
1911 event_base_assert_ok_(base);
1912end:
1913 event_free(ev[0]);
1914 event_free(ev[1]);
1915 event_free(ev[2]);
1916 event_free(ev[3]);
1917 event_free(ev[4]);
1918}

1920static void
1921test_event_base_new(void *ptr)
1922{
1923 struct basic_test_data *data = ptr;
1924 struct event_base *base = 0;
1925 struct event ev1;
1926 struct basic_cb_args args;
1927
1928 int towrite = (int)strlen(TEST1)+1;
1929 int len = write(data->pair[0], TEST1, towrite);
1930
1931 if (len < 0)
1932 tt_abort_perror("initial write");
1933 else if (len != towrite)
1934 tt_abort_printf(("initial write fell short (%d of %d bytes)",
1935 len, towrite));
1936
1937 if (shutdown(data->pair[0], EVUTIL_SHUT_WR))
1938 tt_abort_perror("initial write shutdown");
1939
1940 base = event_base_new();
1941 if (!base)
1942 tt_abort_msg("failed to create event base");
1943
1944 args.eb = base;
1945 args.ev = &ev1;
1946 args.callcount = 0;
1947 event_assign(&ev1, base, data->pair[1],
1948 EV_READ|EV_PERSIST, basic_read_cb, &args);
1949
1950 if (event_add(&ev1, NULL))
1951 tt_abort_perror("initial event_add");
1952
1953 if (event_base_loop(base, 0))
1954 tt_abort_msg("unsuccessful exit from event loop");
1955
1956end:
1957 if (base)
1958 event_base_free(base);
1959}

2091static void
2092test_nonpersist_readd(void)
2093{
2094 struct event ev1, ev2;
2095
2096 setup_test("Re-add nonpersistent events: ");
2097 event_set(&ev1, pair[0], EV_READ, re_add_read_cb, &ev2);
2098 event_set(&ev2, pair[1], EV_READ, re_add_read_cb, &ev1);
2099
2100 if (write(pair[0], "Hello", 5) < 0) {
2101 tt_fail_perror("write(pair[0])");
2102 }
2103
2104 if (write(pair[1], "Hello", 5) < 0) {
2105 tt_fail_perror("write(pair[1])\n");
2106 }
2107
2108 if (event_add(&ev1, NULL) == -1 ||
2109 event_add(&ev2, NULL) == -1) {
2110 test_ok = 0;
2111 }
2112 if (test_ok != 0)
2113 exit(1);
2114 event_loop(EVLOOP_ONCE);
2115 if (test_ok != 2)
2116 exit(1);
2117 /* At this point, we executed both callbacks. Whichever one got
2118 * called first added the second, but the second then immediately got
2119 * deleted before its callback was called. At this point, though, it
2120 * re-added the first.
2121 */
2122 if (!readd_test_event_last_added) {
2123 test_ok = 0;
2124 } else if (readd_test_event_last_added == &ev1) {
2125 if (!event_pending(&ev1, EV_READ, NULL) ||
2126 event_pending(&ev2, EV_READ, NULL))
2127 test_ok = 0;
2128 } else {
2129 if (event_pending(&ev1, EV_READ, NULL) ||
2130 !event_pending(&ev2, EV_READ, NULL))
2131 test_ok = 0;
2132 }
2133
2134 event_del(&ev1);
2135 event_del(&ev2);
2136
2137 cleanup_test();
2138}

2197 event_del(&two.ev);

2202 } else if (npriorities == 2) {

2222/* priority-active-inversion: activate a higher-priority event, and make sure
2223 * it keeps us from running a lower-priority event first. */
2224static int n_pai_calls = 0;
2225static struct event pai_events[3];
2226
2227static void
2228prio_active_inversion_cb(evutil_socket_t fd, short what, void *arg)
2229{
2230 int *call_order = arg;
2231 *call_order = n_pai_calls++;
2232 if (n_pai_calls == 1) {
2233 /* This should activate later, even though it shares a
2234 priority with us. */
2235 event_active(&pai_events[1], EV_READ, 1);
2236 /* This should activate next, since its priority is higher,
2237 even though we activated it second. */
2238 event_active(&pai_events[2], EV_TIMEOUT, 1);
2239 }
2240}

2252 memset(call_order, 0, sizeof(call_order));
2253
2254 for (i=0;i<3;++i) {
2255 event_assign(&pai_events[i], data->base, -1, 0,

2257 }

2888#ifndef _WIN32
2889/* You can't do this test on windows, since dup2 doesn't work on sockets */
2890
2891/* Regression test for our workaround for a fun epoll/linux related bug
2892 * where fd2 = dup(fd1); add(fd2); close(fd2); dup2(fd1,fd2); add(fd2)
2893 * will get you an EEXIST */
2894static void
2895test_dup_fd(void *arg)
2896{
2897 struct basic_test_data *data = arg;
2898 struct event_base *base = data->base;
2899 struct event *ev1=NULL, *ev2=NULL;
2900 int fd, dfd=-1;
2901 int ev1_got, ev2_got;
2902
2903 tt_int_op(write(data->pair[0], "Hello world",
2904 strlen("Hello world")), >, 0);
2905 fd = data->pair[1];
2906
2907 dfd = dup(fd);
2908 tt_int_op(dfd, >=, 0);
2909
2910 ev1 = event_new(base, fd, EV_READ|EV_PERSIST, dfd_cb, &ev1_got);
2911 ev2 = event_new(base, dfd, EV_READ|EV_PERSIST, dfd_cb, &ev2_got);
2912 ev1_got = ev2_got = 0;
2913 event_add(ev1, NULL);
2914 event_add(ev2, NULL);
2915 event_base_loop(base, EVLOOP_ONCE);
2916 tt_int_op(ev1_got, ==, EV_READ);
2917 tt_int_op(ev2_got, ==, EV_READ);
2918
2919 /* Now close and delete dfd then dispatch. We need to do the
2920 * dispatch here so that when we add it later, we think there
2921 * was an intermediate delete. */
2922 close(dfd);
2923 event_del(ev2);
2924 ev1_got = ev2_got = 0;
2925 event_base_loop(base, EVLOOP_ONCE);
2926 tt_want_int_op(ev1_got, ==, EV_READ);
2927 tt_int_op(ev2_got, ==, 0);
2928
2929 /* Re-duplicate the fd. We need to get the same duplicated
2930 * value that we closed to provoke the epoll quirk. Also, we
2931 * need to change the events to write, or else the old lingering
2932 * read event will make the test pass whether the change was
2933 * successful or not. */
2934 tt_int_op(dup2(fd, dfd), ==, dfd);
2935 event_free(ev2);
2936 ev2 = event_new(base, dfd, EV_WRITE|EV_PERSIST, dfd_cb, &ev2_got);
2937 event_add(ev2, NULL);
2938 ev1_got = ev2_got = 0;
2939 event_base_loop(base, EVLOOP_ONCE);
2940 tt_want_int_op(ev1_got, ==, EV_READ);
2941 tt_int_op(ev2_got, ==, EV_WRITE);
2942
2943end:
2944 if (ev1)
2945 event_free(ev1);
2946 if (ev2)
2947 event_free(ev2);
2948 if (dfd >= 0)
2949 close(dfd);
2950}

3023static void
3024test_many_events(void *arg)
3025{
3026 /* Try 70 events that should all be ready at once. This will
3027 * exercise the "resize" code on most of the backends, and will make
3028 * sure that we can get past the 64-handle limit of some windows
3029 * functions. */
3030#define MANY 70
3031
3032 struct basic_test_data *data = arg;
3033 struct event_base *base = data->base;
3034 int one_at_a_time = data->setup_data != NULL;
3035 evutil_socket_t sock[MANY];
3036 struct event *ev[MANY];
3037 int called[MANY];
3038 int i;
3039 int loopflags = EVLOOP_NONBLOCK, evflags=0;
3040 if (one_at_a_time) {
3041 loopflags |= EVLOOP_ONCE;
3042 evflags = EV_PERSIST;
3043 }
3044
3045 memset(sock, 0xff, sizeof(sock));
3046 memset(ev, 0, sizeof(ev));
3047 memset(called, 0, sizeof(called));
3048
3049 for (i = 0; i < MANY; ++i) {
3050 /* We need an event that will hit the backend, and that will
3051 * be ready immediately. "Send a datagram" is an easy
3052 * instance of that. */
3053 sock[i] = socket(AF_INET, SOCK_DGRAM, 0);
3054 tt_assert(sock[i] >= 0);
3055 called[i] = 0;
3056 ev[i] = event_new(base, sock[i], EV_WRITE|evflags,
3057 many_event_cb, &called[i]);
3058 event_add(ev[i], NULL);
3059 if (one_at_a_time)
3060 event_base_loop(base, EVLOOP_NONBLOCK|EVLOOP_ONCE);
3061 }
3062
3063 event_base_loop(base, loopflags);
3064
3065 for (i = 0; i < MANY; ++i) {
3066 if (one_at_a_time)
3067 tt_int_op(called[i], ==, MANY - i + 1);
3068 else
3069 tt_int_op(called[i], ==, 1);
3070 }
3071
3072end:
3073 for (i = 0; i < MANY; ++i) {
3074 if (ev[i])
3075 event_free(ev[i]);
3076 if (sock[i] >= 0)
3077 evutil_closesocket(sock[i]);
3078 }
3079#undef MANY
3080}
